{"title_page": "Ranjit Singh Boparan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ranjit Singh Boparan\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1966|08}}\n| birth_place  = [[Bilston]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], England\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  = \n| restingplace = \n| nationality  = British\n| residence    = \n| education    = \n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = \n| title        = founder and owner of [[2 Sisters Food Group]]\n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| known for    = the \"Chicken King\"\n| boards       = \n| salary       = \n| net worth    = \u00a3544 million (2017)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/sep/28/chicken-king-empire-ranjit-singh-boparan|title=The secretive 'chicken king': inside the empire of Ranjit Singh Boparan|first=Simon|last=Goodley|date=28 September 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 September 2017|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n| spouse       = Baljinder Kaur Boparan\n| parents      = \n| children     = Antonio Singh Boparan \n| relations    = \n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Ranjit Singh Boparan''' (born August 1966) is a British businessman, and the founder and owner of [[2 Sisters Food Group]] with his wife Baljinder Kaur Boparan. Known as the \"Chicken King\" in the West Midlands,<ref name=GuardNrthFoods/> he has an estimated personal fortune of \u00a3544 million.\n\n==Early career==\nBorn in August 1966<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/p8eiEUY_R5Ah0qzKShv8BgGSm_E/appointments |title=Ranjit Singh BOPARAN - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House) |publisher=Beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> in [[Bilston]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], Boparan left school aged 16 with few qualifications.<ref name=GuardNrthFoods/> He started working in a butchers shop, and founded 2 Sisters Food Group in 1993 with a small bank loan.<ref name=GuardNrthFoods/> Still resident today in the West Midlands, he began expanding [[West Bromwich]]-based 2 Sisters Food Group through its holding company Boparan Holdings, which he jointly owns with his wife.\n\n==Boparan Holdings==\nBoparan Holdings is the group company, which owns all of the couple's subsidiary holdings. The Boparans are keen on training and developing their workforce, and are proud of their record of putting employees through [[NVQ]]s on factory and farm production. They are also proud of the high standards of animal welfare and food safety among their partner companies and suppliers,<ref name=BirPostRich>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghampost.net/birmingham-business/richlist/profiles2011/2011/01/23/30-35-ranjit-baljinder-boparan-singh-190million-125m-65233-28032123/ |title=Birmingham Post Rich List, the top 50 wealthiest people in the Midlands |publisher=Birmingham Post |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> although an undercover investigation by [[ITV News]] and ''[[The Guardian]]'' in September 2017 found workers illegally changing the [[Animal slaughter#United Kingdom|slaughter]] dates \u2014 and hence the [[Shelf life|use-by dates]] \u2014 at a 2 Sisters plant in [[West Bromwich]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/sep/28/blood-sweat-deceit-west-midlands-poultry-plant|title=The chicken run: blood, sweat and deceit at a UK poultry plant|first=Simon|last=Goodley\n|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 September 2017|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2 Sisters Food Group===\n{{main|2 Sisters Food Group}}\n2 Sisters Food Group is a Birmingham, England-based food-manufacturing company.\n\nEstablished in 1993 by Ranjit Singh Boparan as a frozen retail cutting operation, it has grown rapidly through acquisition and expanded to cover 36 manufacturing sites in the UK, eight in the Netherlands, five in Ireland and one in Poland.\n\nThe group employs 23,000 people, and annual sales of \u00a33.28 billion. It is listed 9th on the 2017 Sunday Times Top Track 100. It is the largest food company in the UK by turnover.\n\n===Northern Foods===\n{{main|Northern Foods}}\nFollowing a period of asset disposal, on 17 November 2010 [[Northern Foods]] announced it was merging with Irish ready-made meals supplier, [[Greencore]]. According to industry web site, just-food.com, the company's shares rose more than 20% that day. The new company was to be called Essenta,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.just-food.com/analysis/in-the-spotlight-the-greencore-northern-foods-merger_id113251.aspx|title=In the spotlight - The Greencore, Northern Foods merger|publisher=just-food.com|date=|accessdate=17 November 2010}}</ref> with headquarters in Ireland but listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]].\n\nHowever, after building up a 25% share holdings, on 21 January 2011 Boparan announced a \u00a3341M bid to buy Northern Foods,<ref name=\"ft\">[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8a116262-2557-11e0-93ae-00144feab49a.html Boparan wins Northern Foods with \u00a3341m bid] FT.com</ref> which succeeded in gaining sufficient shareholder support to proceed. This resulted in the appointment of Boparan as the company's chairman in April 2011.<ref name=\"insidermedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/yorkshire/50684-boparan-becomes-northern-foods-chairman/|title=Boparan becomes Northern Foods chairman|first=Insider Media|last=Ltd|date=|website=insidermedia.com|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref> On 13 May 2011 the company was delisted from the London Stock Exchange, and taken private under Boparan Holdings.\n\n===FishWorks===\nFishWorks is a seafood restaurant chain, originally started by Mitch Tonks.<ref>{{cite web|author=Terry Durack |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/reviews/his-fishworks-chain-hit-the-rocks-but-mitch-tonks-is-back-with-a-smallfry-operation-thats-making-a-big-splash-904873.html |title=His FishWorks chain hit the rocks, but Mitch Tonks is back with a small-fry operation that's making a big splash |work=The Independent |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Harry Ramsden's===\n{{main|Harry Ramsden's}}\nIn April 2006, [[Compass Group]] sold its specialist airports and railways division SSP for \u00a31,822 million to [[EQT Partners]] of Sweden, including the [[Harry Ramsden's]] [[fish and chip shop]] chain. After attempting a turnaround under new MD Chris Sullivan in 2008,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/57/press/malls-and-hunger-are-a-recipe-for-success/english |title=SSP \u2013 The Food Travel Experts |publisher=Foodtravelexperts.com |date=4 April 2009 |accessdate=26 February 2010 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711015621/http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/57/press/malls-and-hunger-are-a-recipe-for-success/english |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/weekend/Fantastic-feast-for-the-girls.5555537.jp |title=Fantastic feast for the girls \u2013 Blackpool Today |publisher=Blackpoolgazette.co.uk |accessdate=26 February 2010}}</ref> on 19 January 2010 SSP sold Harry Ramsden's to Boparan Ventures Ltd, the private investment vehicle of Boparan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/74/latestnews/the-sale-of-harry-ramsden's |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124062941/http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/74/latestnews/the-sale-of-harry-ramsden's |url-status=dead|archive-date=24 January 2013 |title=SSP \u2013 The Food Travel Experts |publisher=Foodtravelexperts.com |date=15 November 2007 |accessdate=26 February 2010 }}</ref> BVL announced plans to open another 100 units in the next five years, and create 600 new jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/Chicken-magnate-gobbles-up-Harry.5998534.jp |title=Chicken magnate gobbles up Harry Ramsden's with promises of 100 new outlets |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |accessdate=26 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Cinnamon Collection===\nIn January 2016, Boparan Restaurant Holdings (BRH) acquired the three-strong Cinnamon Collection chain of restaurants in London, an upmarket Indian outlet.<ref>http://imbibe.com/news-articles/general/cinnamon-collection-acquired-by-harry-ramsdens-owner/\n/</ref>\n\n===Grove Farm Turkey===\nIn April 2016, the Boparan Private Office acquired Irish Turkey business Grove Farm.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.fwi.co.uk/poultry/2-sisters-ranjit-singh-to-buy-irish-turkey-business.htm/ |title=2 Sisters' Ranjit Singh to buy Irish turkey business - Farmers Weekly |publisher=Fwi.co.uk |date=20 April 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Giraffe Restaurants===\n{{main|Giraffe World Kitchen}}\nIn June 2016, the supermarket chain [[Tesco]] announced that it was to sell its 15-venue [[Giraffe Restaurants]] chain to Boparan Restaurants, for \"an undisclosed sum\", three years after it bought the chain for \u00a350 million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lauren Davidson |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/06/10/tesco-to-offload-giraffe-restaurants-and-its-turkish-business-as/ |title=Tesco to offload Giraffe restaurants and its Turkish business as sell-off continues |publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=10 June 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Bernard Matthews===\n{{main|Bernard Matthews Ltd}}\nIn September 2016, it was announced Singh's Private Office (Boparan Private Office) was to acquire turkey producer Bernard Matthews for \u00a387.5m.<ref>{{cite web|author=Noli DinkovskiNoli Dinkovski, 21 September 2016 |url=http://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/Business-News/Turkey-giant-Bernard-Matthews-purchased-by-Ranjit-Boparan |title=Turkey giant Bernard Matthews purchased by Ranjit Boparan |publisher=Foodmanufacture.co.uk |date=21 September 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ed's Easy Diner===\nIn October 2016, Singh's Private Office added to its restaurant and dining portfolio with the acquisition of part of the 1950s-themed restaurant chain Ed's Easy Diner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecaterer.com/articles/368815/giraffe-owner-buys-33-eds-easy-diners-26-in-administration |title=JavaScript is disabled in your browser. |publisher=Thecaterer.com |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\nBoparan insists on a low public profile and \"doesn't do interviews with the media\".<ref name=GuardNrthFoods>{{cite news| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2011/mar/13/northern-foods-tesco-marks-spencer | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Richard | last=Wachman | title=Ranjit Boparan, the chicken king, looks set to rule the roost at Northern Foods | date=13 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n\n\nRanjit Boparan received an honorary doctorate from [[Nottingham Trent University]] in July 2015, \"in recognition of his significant contribution to the food manufacturing industry, to education and the development of his workforce, and for his philanthropic interests.\"<ref name=FMRShonour>{{cite web| url=http://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/People/2-Sisters-boss-gets-award-from-university | location=London | work=Food Manufacture| first=Mike| last=Stones| title=2 Sisters boss gets award from university | date=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boparan, Ranjit Singh}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:English Sikhs]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ranjit Singh Boparan\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1966|08}}\n| birth_place  = [[Bilston]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], England\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  = \n| restingplace = \n| nationality  = British\n| residence    = \n| education    = \n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = \n| title        = founder and owner of [[2 Sisters Food Group]]\n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| known for    = the \"Chicken King\"\n| boards       = \n| salary       = \n| net worth    = \u00a3544 million (2017)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/sep/28/chicken-king-empire-ranjit-singh-boparan|title=The secretive 'chicken king': inside the empire of Ranjit Singh Boparan|first=Simon|last=Goodley|date=28 September 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 September 2017|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n| spouse       = Baljinder Kaur Boparan\n| parents      = \n| children     = Antonio Singh Boparan \n| relations    = \n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Ranjit Singh Boparan''' (born August 1966) is a British businessman, and the founder and owner of [[2 Sisters Food Group]] with his wife Baljinder Kaur Boparan. Known as the \"Chicken King\" in the West Midlands,<ref name=GuardNrthFoods/> he has an estimated personal fortune of \u00a3544 million.\n\n==Early career==\nBorn in August 1966<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/p8eiEUY_R5Ah0qzKShv8BgGSm_E/appointments |title=Ranjit Singh BOPARAN - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House) |publisher=Beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> in [[Bilston]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], Boparan left school aged 16 with few qualifications.<ref name=GuardNrthFoods/> He started working in a butchers shop, and founded 2 Sisters Food Group in 1993 with a small bank loan.<ref name=GuardNrthFoods/> Still resident today in the West Midlands, he began expanding [[West Bromwich]]-based 2 Sisters Food Group through its holding company Boparan Holdings, which he jointly owns with his wife.\n\n==Boparan Holdings==\nBoparan Holdings is the group company, which owns all of the couple's subsidiary holdings. The Boparans are keen on training and developing their workforce, and are proud of their record of putting employees through [[NVQ]]s on factory and farm production. They are also proud of the high standards of animal welfare and food safety among their partner companies and suppliers,<ref name=BirPostRich>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghampost.net/birmingham-business/richlist/profiles2011/2011/01/23/30-35-ranjit-baljinder-boparan-singh-190million-125m-65233-28032123/ |title=Birmingham Post Rich List, the top 50 wealthiest people in the Midlands |publisher=Birmingham Post |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> although an undercover investigation by [[ITV News]] and ''[[The Guardian]]'' in September 2017 found workers illegally changing the [[Animal slaughter#United Kingdom|slaughter]] dates \u2014 and hence the [[Shelf life|use-by dates]] \u2014 at a 2 Sisters plant in [[West Bromwich]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/sep/28/blood-sweat-deceit-west-midlands-poultry-plant|title=The chicken run: blood, sweat and deceit at a UK poultry plant|first=Simon|last=Goodley\n|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 September 2017|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2 Sisters Food Group===\n{{main|2 Sisters Food Group}}\n2 Sisters Food Group is a Birmingham, England-based food-manufacturing company.\n\nEstablished in 1993 by Ranjit Singh Boparan as a frozen retail cutting operation, it has grown rapidly through acquisition and expanded to cover 36 manufacturing sites in the UK, eight in the Netherlands, five in Ireland and one in Poland.\n\nThe group employs 23,000 people, and annual sales of \u00a33.28 billion. It is listed 9th on the 2017 Sunday Times Top Track 100. It is the largest food company in the UK by turnover.\n\n===Northern Foods===\n{{main|Northern Foods}}\nFollowing a period of asset disposal, on 17 November 2010 [[Northern Foods]] announced it was merging with Irish ready-made meals supplier, [[Greencore]]. According to industry web site, just-food.com, the company's shares rose more than 20% that day. The new company was to be called Essenta,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.just-food.com/analysis/in-the-spotlight-the-greencore-northern-foods-merger_id113251.aspx|title=In the spotlight - The Greencore, Northern Foods merger|publisher=just-food.com|date=|accessdate=17 November 2010}}</ref> with headquarters in Ireland but listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]].\n\nHowever, after building up a 25% share holdings, on 21 January 2011 Boparan announced a \u00a3341M bid to buy Northern Foods,<ref name=\"ft\">[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8a116262-2557-11e0-93ae-00144feab49a.html Boparan wins Northern Foods with \u00a3341m bid] FT.com</ref> which succeeded in gaining sufficient shareholder support to proceed. This resulted in the appointment of Boparan as the company's chairman in April 2011.<ref name=\"insidermedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/yorkshire/50684-boparan-becomes-northern-foods-chairman/|title=Boparan becomes Northern Foods chairman|first=Insider Media|last=Ltd|date=|website=insidermedia.com|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref> On 13 May 2011 the company was delisted from the London Stock Exchange, and taken private under Boparan Holdings.\n\n===FishWorks===\nFishWorks is a seafood restaurant chain, originally started by Mitch Tonks.<ref>{{cite web|author=Terry Durack |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/reviews/his-fishworks-chain-hit-the-rocks-but-mitch-tonks-is-back-with-a-smallfry-operation-thats-making-a-big-splash-904873.html |title=His FishWorks chain hit the rocks, but Mitch Tonks is back with a small-fry operation that's making a big splash |work=The Independent |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Harry Ramsden's===\n{{main|Harry Ramsden's}}\nIn April 2006, [[Compass Group]] sold its specialist airports and railways division SSP for \u00a31,822 million to [[EQT Partners]] of Sweden, including the [[Harry Ramsden's]] [[fish and chip shop]] chain. After attempting a turnaround under new MD Chris Sullivan in 2008,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/57/press/malls-and-hunger-are-a-recipe-for-success/english |title=SSP \u2013 The Food Travel Experts |publisher=Foodtravelexperts.com |date=4 April 2009 |accessdate=26 February 2010 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711015621/http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/57/press/malls-and-hunger-are-a-recipe-for-success/english |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/weekend/Fantastic-feast-for-the-girls.5555537.jp |title=Fantastic feast for the girls \u2013 Blackpool Today |publisher=Blackpoolgazette.co.uk |accessdate=26 February 2010}}</ref> on 19 January 2010 SSP sold Harry Ramsden's to Boparan Ventures Ltd, the private investment vehicle of Boparan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/74/latestnews/the-sale-of-harry-ramsden's |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124062941/http://www.foodtravelexperts.com/newsarticle/74/latestnews/the-sale-of-harry-ramsden's |url-status=dead|archive-date=24 January 2013 |title=SSP \u2013 The Food Travel Experts |publisher=Foodtravelexperts.com |date=15 November 2007 |accessdate=26 February 2010 }}</ref> BVL announced plans to open another 100 units in the next five years, and create 600 new jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/Chicken-magnate-gobbles-up-Harry.5998534.jp |title=Chicken magnate gobbles up Harry Ramsden's with promises of 100 new outlets |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |accessdate=26 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Cinnamon Collection===\nIn January 2016, Boparan Restaurant Holdings (BRH) acquired the three-strong Cinnamon Collection chain of restaurants in London, an upmarket Indian outlet.<ref>http://imbibe.com/news-articles/general/cinnamon-collection-acquired-by-harry-ramsdens-owner/\n/</ref>\n\n===Grove Farm Turkey===\nIn April 2016, the Boparan Private Office acquired Irish Turkey business Grove Farm.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.fwi.co.uk/poultry/2-sisters-ranjit-singh-to-buy-irish-turkey-business.htm/ |title=2 Sisters' Ranjit Singh to buy Irish turkey business - Farmers Weekly |publisher=Fwi.co.uk |date=20 April 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Giraffe Restaurants===\n{{main|Giraffe World Kitchen}}\nIn June 2016, the supermarket chain [[Tesco]] announced that it was to sell its 15-venue [[Giraffe Restaurants]] chain to Boparan Restaurants, for \"an undisclosed sum\", three years after it bought the chain for \u00a350 million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lauren Davidson |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/06/10/tesco-to-offload-giraffe-restaurants-and-its-turkish-business-as/ |title=Tesco to offload Giraffe restaurants and its Turkish business as sell-off continues |publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=10 June 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Bernard Matthews===\n{{main|Bernard Matthews Ltd}}\nIn September 2016, it was announced Singh's Private Office (Boparan Private Office) was to acquire turkey producer Bernard Matthews for \u00a387.5m.<ref>{{cite web|author=Noli DinkovskiNoli Dinkovski, 21 September 2016 |url=http://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/Business-News/Turkey-giant-Bernard-Matthews-purchased-by-Ranjit-Boparan |title=Turkey giant Bernard Matthews purchased by Ranjit Boparan |publisher=Foodmanufacture.co.uk |date=21 September 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ed's Easy Diner===\nIn October 2016, Singh's Private Office added to its restaurant and dining portfolio with the acquisition of part of the 1950s-themed restaurant chain Ed's Easy Diner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecaterer.com/articles/368815/giraffe-owner-buys-33-eds-easy-diners-26-in-administration |title=JavaScript is disabled in your browser. |publisher=Thecaterer.com |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\nBoparan insists on a low public profile and \"doesn't do interviews with the media\".<ref name=GuardNrthFoods>{{cite news| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2011/mar/13/northern-foods-tesco-marks-spencer | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Richard | last=Wachman | title=Ranjit Boparan, the chicken king, looks set to rule the roost at Northern Foods | date=13 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, the couple's then 19-year-old son, Antonio, was prosecuted after his [[Range Rover Sport]] left one-year-old Cerys Edwards with severe brain damage after his car, which was travelling at {{convert|70|mph}} on the wrong side of a {{convert|30|mph}} single-track road,<ref name=DMail554249>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-554249/How-cars-black-box-trapped-speeding-Rich-List-heir-left-baby-paralysed-Range-Rover-crash.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=How car's black box trapped speeding Rich List heir who left baby paralysed in Range Rover crash | date=3 April 2008}}</ref> hit the [[Jeep]] her parents were driving. He was the first person convicted under English and Welsh law from evidence recovered from his car's [[Event Data Recorder]] system, concealed in the driver's [[airbag]].<ref name=DMail554249/> In April 2008, Antonio Boparan was sentenced to 21 months in jail for [[dangerous driving]], at Birmingham Crown Court. In February 2012, Cerys Edwards' family was awarded \u00a35M, and a sum of \u00a3450k per annum every year for her life for Cerys' care, from Boparan's insurance company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-17139275|title=Cerys Edwards injured by speeding driver awarded \u00a35m|publisher=BBC West Mildands|date=23 February 2012|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref> Cerys died at Birmingham Children's Hospital on 17 October 2015, aged 9.<ref>{{cite news|last=McLelland |first=Euan |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3280592/Girl-suffered-catastrophic-injuries-baby-speeding-teenage-heir-130million-fortune-hit-parents-car-dies-hospital-nine-years-later.html |title=Cerys Edwards who was injuries as baby dies nine years after car crash with Antonio Boparan |work=Daily Mail |date=20 October 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Antonio Boparan was involved in a Birmingham bar brawl which left a man blinded. Antonio later admitted in court to inflicting actual bodily harm and violent disorder.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2942453/Food-tycoon-s-son-left-baby-severely-brain-damaged-horror-crash-facing-jail-second-time-bar-brawl-left-man-blinded.html| location=London | work=The Daily Mail | first=Jenny | last=Awford |title=Harry Ramsden's owner's son who left a baby severely brain damaged in horror crash is facing jail for the second time over bar brawl which left a man blinded.|date=6 February 2015}}</ref> He received a 12 months prison sentence.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/antonio-singh-boporan-man-baby-brain-damage-dangerous-driving-director-2-sisters-food-group-food-a7871306.html|title=Criminal who left a baby brain damaged becomes director of one of Britain's biggest food companies|author=|date=1 August 2017|website=independent.co.uk|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref> \nMarch 2019,  The millionaire's son was today (March 7) sentenced to 18 months behind bars over the death of the youngster.\n\nRanjit Boparan received an honorary doctorate from [[Nottingham Trent University]] in July 2015, \"in recognition of his significant contribution to the food manufacturing industry, to education and the development of his workforce, and for his philanthropic interests.\"<ref name=FMRShonour>{{cite web| url=http://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/People/2-Sisters-boss-gets-award-from-university | location=London | work=Food Manufacture| first=Mike| last=Stones| title=2 Sisters boss gets award from university | date=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boparan, Ranjit Singh}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:English Sikhs]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:360e:a00:b827:ef39:d16:534c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFamily and personal life:Removed unnecessary content regarding his son which is not about Ranjit Boparan.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranjit_Singh_Boparan"}
{"title_page": "Ninon Guillon-Romarin", "text_new": "{{short description|French athlete}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = Ninon Guillon-Romarin\n| birth_name  = \n| image       = Guillon-romarinreims14.JPG\n| caption     = Ninon Guillon-Romarin in 2014\n| nationality = French\n| sport       = Athletics\n| event       = Pole vault\n| club        = \n| collegeteam =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1995|4|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| height      = 1.63 m<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.tarragona2018.cat/en/ATH/athlete/18013371|title=2018 Med Games bio|accessdate=6 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707034641/http://results.tarragona2018.cat/en/ATH/athlete/18013371|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| weight      = 53 kg\n}}\n\n'''Ninon Guillon-Romarin''' (born 15 April 1995) is a French [[pole vault]]er.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/athletes/france/ninon-guillon-romarin-266148 |title=Ninon Guillon-Romarin |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref> She competed in the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's pole vault|women's pole vault]] at the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/iaaf-world-championships-london-2017-5151/results/women/pole-vault/qualification/startlist#resultheader |title=Pole Vault women |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref> She represented France in [[2017 European Team Championships]], where she was 3rd with a jump of 4.45m in [[Lille]]. At the [[2017 European Athletics U23 Championships]] she finished in 5th place with a jump of 4.35m.<ref>[http://www.european-athletics.org/competitions/european-athletics-u23-championships/history/year=2017/athletics/event/womens-pole-vault/phase=atw072100/doc=series.html Final results]</ref>\n\nShe holds the [[List of French records in athletics|french indoor record]] with a jump of 4.72 m, set on 25 February 2018 in [[Clermont-Ferrand]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.trackandlife.fr/all-star-perche-histoire-de-perche-sest-envolee-a-clermont-ferrand/|title=All Star Perche : L'histoire s'en souviendra - Track and Life|date=25 February 2018|work=Track and Life|access-date=25 February 2018|language=fr-FR}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{iaaf name|266148}}\n\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions Pole Vault Women}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guillon-Romarin, Ninon}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French female pole vaulters]]\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships athletes for France]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2018 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists in athletics]]\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French athlete}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = Ninon Guillon-Romarin\n| birth_name  = \n| image       = Guillon-romarinreims14.JPG\n| caption     = Ninon Guillon-Romarin in 2014\n| nationality = French\n| sport       = Athletics\n| event       = Pole vault\n| club        = \n| collegeteam =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1995|4|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| height      = 1.63 m<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.tarragona2018.cat/en/ATH/athlete/18013371|title=2018 Med Games bio|accessdate=6 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707034641/http://results.tarragona2018.cat/en/ATH/athlete/18013371|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| weight      = 53 kg\n}}\n\n'''Ninon Guillon-Romarin''' (born 15 April 1995) is a French [[pole vault]]er.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/athletes/france/ninon-guillon-romarin-266148 |title=Ninon Guillon-Romarin |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref> She competed in the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's pole vault|women's pole vault]] at the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/iaaf-world-championships-london-2017-5151/results/women/pole-vault/qualification/startlist#resultheader |title=Pole Vault women |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref> She represented France in [[2017 European Team Championships]], where she was 3rd with a jump of 4.45m in [[Lille]]. At the [[2017 European Athletics U23 Championships]] she finished in 5th place with a jump of 4.35m.<ref>[http://www.european-athletics.org/competitions/european-athletics-u23-championships/history/year=2017/athletics/event/womens-pole-vault/phase=atw072100/doc=series.html Final results]</ref>\n\nShe holds the [[List of French records in athletics|french indoor record]] with a jump of 4.72 m, set on 25 February 2018 in [[Clermont-Ferrand]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.trackandlife.fr/all-star-perche-histoire-de-perche-sest-envolee-a-clermont-ferrand/|title=All Star Perche : L'histoire s'en souviendra - Track and Life|date=25 February 2018|work=Track and Life|access-date=25 February 2018|language=fr-FR}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{iaaf name|266148}}\n\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions Pole Vault Women}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guillon-Romarin, Ninon}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French female pole vaulters]]\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships athletes for France]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2018 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists in athletics]]\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninon_Guillon-Romarin"}
{"title_page": "Deaf studies", "text_new": "{{About|the studies of deaf culture, art, language, and people|the education of deaf students as well as teachers of the deaf|Deaf education|deafness as a medical condition|hearing loss}}\n[[File:Ethiopian Sign Language consersation (cropped).jpg|thumb|250px|The emergence of Deaf Studies was facilitated by the revelation that signed languages are bona fide languages.<ref name=\":0\" />]]\n'''Deaf studies''' are academic disciplines concerned with the study of the deaf social life of human groups and individuals. These constitute an interdisciplinary field that integrates contents, critiques, and methodologies from anthropology, cultural studies, economics, geography, history, political science, psychology, social studies, and sociology, among others.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The SAGE Deaf Studies Encyclopedia|last=Gertz|first=Genie|last2=Boudreault|first2=Patrick|date=2016|publisher=SAGE Publications|year=|isbn=978-1-4833-4647-2|location=Thousand Oaks, CA|pages=272}}</ref> The field focuses on the language, culture, and lives of the deaf from the social instead of the medical perspective.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Sign Language in Action|last=Napier|first=Jemina|last2=Leeson|first2=Lorraine|date=2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=|isbn=978-1-137-30975-4|location=New York|pages=19}}</ref>\n\nDeaf studies are also described as those comprising the scientific study of the deaf-related aspects of the world.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/student/career-planning/az-careers/deaf-studies-671539.html Deaf studies, ''From Which Course?'', 30.6, Friday, 1 February 2008]</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nDeaf studies emerged with the recognition that deaf people have a culture and that such culture is unique, requiring alternative ways of understanding this segment of the population outside of pathological frameworks.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Innovations in Deaf Studies: The Role of Deaf Scholars|last=Kusters|first=Annelies|last2=Meulder|first2=Maartje De|last3=O'Brien|first3=Dai|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=9780190612184|location=New York|pages=88}}</ref> The [[University of Bristol]] began using the term \"deaf studies\" in 1984 after the founding of the [[Centre for Deaf Studies, Bristol|Centre for Deaf Studies]] in 1968.<ref name=\":1\" /> Scholars began identifying themselves with the field,<ref name=\":1\" /> particularly after degree-granting programs in Deaf Studies began to emerge in the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States]] from the late 1970s to the 1980s.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first master's degree on Deaf Studies was introduced at the University of Bristol in 1992.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Areas ==\nStudying the lives of those who are deaf include learning about their culture, sign language, history and their human rights. Being involved in \"Deaf Studies\" means focusing on the sociological, historical and linguistic aspects of the '''deaf''' and hearing impaired. Within this, it prepares individuals to work with the '''deaf''' and hearing impaired. Those who participate and join this field of study are involved with promoting the change of views and perspectives of the larger society regarding Deaf people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gallaudet.edu/american-sign-language-and-deaf-studies/outcomes---careers.html|title=Outcomes and Careers - Gallaudet University|last=University|first=Gallaudet|website=gallaudet.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211082522/https://www.gallaudet.edu/american-sign-language-and-deaf-studies/outcomes---careers.html|archive-date=2017-02-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> Becoming involved in the Deaf Community takes a while, but the time and effort goes a long way.\n\n'''Deaf studies''' includes the study of:\n*[[Deaf culture]]\n*[[List of deaf people|Deaf people]]\n*[[Sign language]]\n*[[Deaf history]]\n*[[Body Language]]\n*[[Social Skills]]\n*[[Personal Skills]]\n\n==University-based deaf studies centers==\n* United States\n** Masters offered\n***[[Gallaudet University]], Washington, D.C.\n***[[Lamar University]], Beaumont, Texas\n***[[California State University, Northridge]], Northridge, California\n***[[McDaniel College]], Westminster, Maryland\n** Bachelors offered\n***[[Boston University]], Boston, MA\n*** [[California State University, Northridge]], Northridge, California\n*** [[California State University, Sacramento]], Sacramento, California\n*** [[Columbia College Chicago]], Chicago, Illinois\n*** [[Gallaudet University]], Washington, D.C. \n*** [[Lamar University]], Beaumont, Texas\n*** [[Towson University]], Towson, Maryland\n*** [[Utah Valley University]], Orem, Utah\n*** [[Keuka College]] Keuka Park, New York\n** State Certifications\n*** [[Texas Woman's University]], Denton, Texas (offers Masters in Deaf Education)\n***[[Cincinnati State]], Community College in Cincinnati Ohio (Offers masters, Interpreter Training Program ITP) \n** Associate in Arts offered\n*** [[College of the Holy Cross]], Worcester, MA\n*** [[Ohlone College]], Fremont, CA\n*** [[Utah Valley University]], Orem, Utah\n* United Kingdom\n** [[University of Central Lancashire]], Lancashire, England\n** [[Centre for Deaf Studies, Bristol]], [[University of Bristol]], Bristol\n** [[University of Wolverhampton]], Wolverhampton, England <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlv.ac.uk/about-us/our-schools-and-institutes/faculty-of-social-sciences/school-of-social-historical-and-political-studies/undergraduate-subject-areas/interpreting-and-deaf-studies/deaf-studies/|title=Deaf Studies - University of Wolverhampton|last=University|first=Wolverhampton|website=wlv.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-04-10}}</ref> \n* New Zealand\n** [[Victoria University of Wellington]]\n* Germany\n** [[Humboldt University]], Berlin <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hu-berlin.de/en/studies/counselling/course-catalogue/programme-descriptions/deafkombi|title=Deaf Studies - Humboldt University|last=University|first=Humboldt|website=hu-berlin.de|language=en|access-date=2017-04-10}}</ref> \n* Hong Kong\n** Centre for Sign Linguistics and Deaf Studies, [[The Chinese University of Hong Kong]], Hong Kong <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cslds.org/v3/|title=Centre for Sign Linguistics and Deaf Studies |website=cslds.org|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n* India\n**[[National Institute of Speech and Hearing]], Kerala, India (offers Degree in Deaf Education)\n* The Netherlands\n** Visual Language, Signs and Gestures, [[Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics]], Nijmegen\n* Czech republic\n** [http://ujkn.ff.cuni.cz/cs/ Ustav jazyku a komunikace neslysicich (Institute of Deaf Studies)], [[Faculty of Arts, Charles University in Prague|Faculty of Arts, Charles University]], Prague\n\n==National and transnational Deaf studies centers==\n* New Zealand\n** [[Kelston Deaf Education Centre]]\n* Philippines\n** [[De La Salle\u2013College of Saint Benilde#School of Deaf Education and Applied Studies|School of Deaf Education and Applied Studies]], De La Salle\u2013College of Saint Benilde\n\n==Deaf studies associations==\n* United States\n** [[CSUN Deaf Studies Association]], Northridge, California\n* United Kingdom\n** [[The British Association of Teachers of the Deaf]]\n\n==Deaf-related major projects==\n* India\n** [[Deafchild India]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Area studies}}\n* ''[[American Annals of the Deaf]]''\n* ''[[Journal of Deaf Studies and Deaf Education]]''\n* [[Deaf Bibliography]] for a categorised list of publications in the field since 1984\n*[[Deaf history]]\n* [[Deafhood]]\n* ''[[Sign Language Studies]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deaf Studies}}\n[[Category:Deaf studies| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the studies of deaf culture, art, language, and people|the education of deaf students as well as teachers of the deaf|Deaf education|deafness as a medical condition|hearing loss}}\n[[File:Ethiopian Sign