{"title_page": "What Doesn't Kill You (film)", "text_new": "{{for|other works with similar titles|What does not kill me makes me stronger (disambiguation){{!}}What does not kill me makes me stronger}}\n{{Infobox film \n| name           = What Doesn't Kill You\n| image          = What_doesnt_kill_you_film.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| screenplay     = [[Donnie Wahlberg]] <br />[[Brian Goodman]] <br />Paul T. Murray\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] \n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] \n* [[Amanda Peet]] \n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] \n* [[Max Martini]] \n* [[Angela Featherstone]]\n}}\n| director       = [[Brian Goodman]]\n| producer       = Marc Frydman <br />Peter R. McIntosh <br />[[Rod Lurie]] <br />[[Bob Yari]] <br />[[Rand Ravich]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = Battleplan Productions<br />Cold Spring Pictures<br />[[The Montecito Picture Company]]<br />[[Bob Yari|Bob Yari Productions]]<br />Alphaville Films\n| distributor    = [[Yari Film Group|Yari Film Group Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2008|12|12}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''What Doesn't Kill You''''' is a 2008 American crime drama loosely based on the true life story of the film's director [[Brian Goodman]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=50984|title=Exclusive: Brian Goodman Faces What Doesn't Kill You|date=2008-12-10|work=comingsoon.net|accessdate=2009-10-23}}</ref> detailing his own exploits involved with [[South Boston, Boston|South Boston]]'s [[Irish Mob]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/entertainment/movies/dvd/view.bg?articleid=1168036|title=What Doesn't Kill You Blurb by Dave Wedge|date=2009-04-26|work=BostonHerald.com|accessdate=2009-10-23}}</ref> Starring [[Ethan Hawke]] and [[Mark Ruffalo]], it premiered at the [[2008 Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=story&id=2652&articleid=VR1117991493|title=Toronto Film Festival lineup 2008|date=2008-08-19|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2009-10-19}}</ref> and was released on a very small scale in December 2008 due to the collapse of its distributor [[Yari Film Group]] and NBC adapted TV series ''[[Crisis (TV series)|Crisis]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997332 |title=Bob Yari crashes into Chapter 11|date=2008-12-12|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2009-10-19 | first=Michael | last=Fleming}}</ref> The title alludes to the [[Nietzsche]] quote {{lang|de|[[Twilight of the Idols#Cultural impact|Was mich nicht umbringt, macht mich st\u00e4rker]]}} (What does not kill me makes me stronger).Also SSSniper wolf edited the film\n\n==Premise==\nHawke and Ruffalo play childhood friends Paulie and Brian, who are forced to survive on the tough streets of South Boston through a life of petty thievery. They join a local gang of criminals, but Brian finds it hard to reconcile his work and friendship with Paulie and his relationship with his wife ([[Amanda Peet]]) and sons.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] as Brian Reilly\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] as Paulie McDougan\n* [[Amanda Peet]] as Stacy Reilly\n* [[Will Lyman]] as Sully\n* [[Brian Goodman]] as Pat Kelly\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as Detective Moran\n* [[Angela Featherstone]] as Katie\n* Brian Connolly as Sean\n* [[Lindsey McKeon]] as Nicole\n* Eddie J Fernandez as Swat team leader 1\n* [[Michael yebba|Michael Yebba]] as Round Man\n* Michael Elian as FBI/HRT Swat sniper team 1\n* Brett G Smith as FBI/HRT Swat commander \n* [[Max Martini]] as FBI/HRT Swat (M4 Carbine)\n* [[Candice Accola]] as teenage hostage\n* [[Rich Skinner]] as Chappy\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 65% based on 34 reviews.<ref>{{cite web | title= What Doesn't Kill You Movie |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/what_doesnt_kill_you/ | website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate= 2019-11-19 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a score of 71 out of 100 based on reviews from 10 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | title= What Doesn't Kill You Reviews |url= http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/whatdoesntkillyou | work= [[Metacritic]] | accessdate= 2019-11-19 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1133991}}\n* {{mojo title|whatdoesntkillyou}}\n* {{metacritic film|what-doesnt-kill-you}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|what_doesnt_kill_you}}\n\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2000s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s heist films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American heist films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about the Irish Mob]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Crime films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:2008 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other works with similar titles|What does not kill me makes me stronger (disambiguation){{!}}What does not kill me makes me stronger}}\n{{Infobox film \n| name           = What Doesn't Kill You\n| image          = What_doesnt_kill_you_film.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| screenplay     = [[Donnie Wahlberg]] <br />[[Brian Goodman]] <br />Paul T. Murray\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] \n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] \n* [[Amanda Peet]] \n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] \n* [[Max Martini]] \n* [[Angela Featherstone]]\n}}\n| director       = [[Brian Goodman]]\n| producer       = Marc Frydman <br />Peter R. McIntosh <br />[[Rod Lurie]] <br />[[Bob Yari]] <br />[[Rand Ravich]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = Battleplan Productions<br />Cold Spring Pictures<br />[[The Montecito Picture Company]]<br />[[Bob Yari|Bob Yari Productions]]<br />Alphaville Films\n| distributor    = [[Yari Film Group|Yari Film Group Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2008|12|12}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''What Doesn't Kill You''''' is a 2008 American crime drama loosely based on the true life story of the film's director [[Brian Goodman]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=50984|title=Exclusive: Brian Goodman Faces What Doesn't Kill You|date=2008-12-10|work=comingsoon.net|accessdate=2009-10-23}}</ref> detailing his own exploits involved with [[South Boston, Boston|South Boston]]'s [[Irish Mob]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/entertainment/movies/dvd/view.bg?articleid=1168036|title=What Doesn't Kill You Blurb by Dave Wedge|date=2009-04-26|work=BostonHerald.com|accessdate=2009-10-23}}</ref> Starring [[Ethan Hawke]] and [[Mark Ruffalo]], it premiered at the [[2008 Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=story&id=2652&articleid=VR1117991493|title=Toronto Film Festival lineup 2008|date=2008-08-19|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2009-10-19}}</ref> and was released on a very small scale in December 2008 due to the collapse of its distributor [[Yari Film Group]] and NBC adapted TV series ''[[Crisis (TV series)|Crisis]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997332 |title=Bob Yari crashes into Chapter 11|date=2008-12-12|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2009-10-19 | first=Michael | last=Fleming}}</ref> The title alludes to the [[Nietzsche]] quote {{lang|de|[[Twilight of the Idols#Cultural impact|Was mich nicht umbringt, macht mich st\u00e4rker]]}} (What does not kill me makes me stronger).\n\n==Premise==\nHawke and Ruffalo play childhood friends Paulie and Brian, who are forced to survive on the tough streets of South Boston through a life of petty thievery. They join a local gang of criminals, but Brian finds it hard to reconcile his work and friendship with Paulie and his relationship with his wife ([[Amanda Peet]]) and sons.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] as Brian Reilly\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] as Paulie McDougan\n* [[Amanda Peet]] as Stacy Reilly\n* [[Will Lyman]] as Sully\n* [[Brian Goodman]] as Pat Kelly\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as Detective Moran\n* [[Angela Featherstone]] as Katie\n* Brian Connolly as Sean\n* [[Lindsey McKeon]] as Nicole\n* Eddie J Fernandez as Swat team leader 1\n* [[Michael yebba|Michael Yebba]] as Round Man\n* Michael Elian as FBI/HRT Swat sniper team 1\n* Brett G Smith as FBI/HRT Swat commander \n* [[Max Martini]] as FBI/HRT Swat (M4 Carbine)\n* [[Candice Accola]] as teenage hostage\n* [[Rich Skinner]] as Chappy\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 65% based on 34 reviews.<ref>{{cite web | title= What Doesn't Kill You Movie |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/what_doesnt_kill_you/ | website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate= 2019-11-19 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a score of 71 out of 100 based on reviews from 10 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | title= What Doesn't Kill You Reviews |url= http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/whatdoesntkillyou | work= [[Metacritic]] | accessdate= 2019-11-19 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1133991}}\n* {{mojo title|whatdoesntkillyou}}\n* {{metacritic film|what-doesnt-kill-you}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|what_doesnt_kill_you}}\n\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2000s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s heist films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American heist films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about the Irish Mob]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Crime films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:2008 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "47.41.50.245", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/What_Doesn%27t_Kill_You_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Guilty?", "text_new": "{{short description|1930 film}}\n{{For|the French film|Guilty? (1951 film)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Guilty?\n| image          = Guilty? (1930 film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[George B. Seitz]]\n| producer       = [[Harry Cohn]]\n| writer         = [[Dorothy Howell (writer)|Dorothy Howell]]\n| starring       = [[Virginia Valli]] and [[John Holland (actor born 1899)|John Holland]]\n| cinematography = Ted Tetzlaff\n| editing        = Leon Barsha\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1930|3|3}}\n| runtime        = 67 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''Guilty?''''' is a 1930 American [[Pre-Code Hollywood|pre-Code]] [[drama film]] directed by [[George B. Seitz]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/94003/Guilty-/overview|title=NY Times: Guilty?|accessdate=June 21, 2011|work=NY Times}}</ref>{{dead link|date=June 2019}}\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Virginia Valli]] as Carolyn\n* [[John Holland (actor born 1899)|John Holland]] as Bob Lee\n* [[John St. Polis]] as Polk\n* [[Lydia Knott]] as Martha\n* [[Erville Alderson]] as Lee\n* [[Richard Carlyle (actor, born 1879)|Richard Carlyle]] as Dr. Bennett\n* [[Clarence Muse]] as Jefferson\n* [[Eddie Clayton]] as Jerry\n* Robert T. Haines as Prosecuting Attorney\n* [[Frank Fanning]] as Warden\n* [[Edward Cecil (actor)|Edward Cecil]] as Judge\n* [[Gertrude Howard]] as Lucy\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0020943|title=Guilty?}}\n\n{{George B. Seitz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guilty?}}\n[[Category:1930 films]]\n[[Category:1930 drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by George B. Seitz]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]